%main.work
    %section.summary
        %p.large Tuft & Needle changed the mattress industry by creating a new way to buy mattresses. Our try-at-home, bed-in-a-box model with free shipping and easy returns raised the bar on customer support and convenience. And while we created an industry that has been steadily stealing away market share from the traditional players, there’s still a majority of shoppers who buy mattresses through traditional means. Our merger with Serta Simmons Bedding (SSB) is our attempt to change the way traditional mattress companies do business, making it a better experience for customers. 
        %p.large In preparation for the merger, we kicked off a preliminary study to determine the most effective strategy for making quick, positive changes to the customer experience for Serta and Beautyrest.

    %section
        %h2.s4 Identifying the problems
        %p After conducting some initial research and an audit of Serta’s and Beautyrest’s websites, products, and services, we determined that several things are holding the brands back from having the type of customer experience that modern shoppers have come to expect.
        %ol.no-image
            %li Too many product offerings with unclear differentiation
            %li Poor customer support, especially around warranty claims and returns
            %li Cluttered, complicated websites with confusing information architecture and convoluted purchase paths. 

    %section 
        %h2.s4 The configurator: a simplification of choice
        %p We had many multidisciplinary brainstorming sessions generating and evaluating various solutions. To address numbers 1 and 3, we decided that the best first step was to streamline the product offerings by removing hundreds of products from the online shopping experience and merging the best-selling SKUs into a few distinct, configurable products. 
        %p Taking inspiration from the automotive and tech industries, we experimented with creating product detail pages that would allow us to offer multiple variations of a product but display them to the user in a simplified, benefit-based decision flow. We called this new type of product page a “configurator.”
